<HEADLINE>
<P>
DESPITE SMITH'S 32 POINTS, CLIPPERS LOSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PORTLAND, Ore. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Charles Smith scored 32 points and backup center Ken Bannister, starting in 
place of ailing Benoit Benjamin, had 21, but the Clippers still lost to the 
Portland Trail Blazers, 126-102, Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
Benjamin suffered an allergy reaction and did not play. 
</P>
<P>
For Portland, Clyde Drexler scored 24 points and Terry Porter had his second 
triple-double of the season as the Clippers fell to 18-58. 
</P>
<P>
Drexler scored 10 points in the second quarter, helping the Trail Blazers build 
a 66-42 halftime lead. 
</P>
<P>
Porter finished the game with 10 points, 15 assists and 10 rebounds for 
Portland, which improved its lead over the Dallas Mavericks to three games with 
six to play in the race for the eighth and final Western Conference playoff 
spot. 
</P>
<P>
The 32 points were a career high for Smith. 
</P>
<P>
The Trail Blazers built a 30-22 lead after one quarter, then outscored the 
Clippers, 16-8, in the first six minutes of the second period. Porter and 
Kersey had consecutive layups to give Portland a 46-30 lead. 
</P>
<P>
Portland took its largest lead, 70-44, early in the third quarter before the 
Clippers used a 28-16 spurt to close the gap to 86-72. But that was close as 
the Clippers could get in the second half. 
</P>
<P>
Portland got balanced scoring. Kevin Duckworth had 21 points, Jerome Kersey 18 
and the bench 45. Clipper reserves had 27. 
</P>
<P>
For Porter, it was his sixth career triple-double. 
</P>
<P>
"We really tried to concentrate and get off to a good start, which we did," he 
said. "We weren't going to let them get back into it like we did before." 
</P>
<P>
Porter was referring to a 133-123 loss to the Clippers at the Sports Arena last 
Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
The Trail Blazers outrebounded the Clippers, 50-34, and blocked 11 shots, 
including three by Sam Bowie, who missed the previous nine games with a 
sprained ankle. 
</P>
<P>
"Danny Young and Sam Bowie played well off the bench," Portland Coach Rick 
Adelman said. "I was especially pleased to see Sam move as well as he did after 
the long layoff. Jerry Sichting was also moving well after such a long layoff 
and I want to give him some time before the playoffs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
