<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TV &amp; VIDEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a week in which all three network news anchors were in Cuba for Soviet 
leader Mikhail Gorbachev's visit, Peter Jennings' "ABC World News Tonight" 
narrowly edged Dan Rather's "CBS Evening News" and won the week's ratings, A. 
C. Nielsen Co. figures showed Tuesday. Jennings' broadcast averaged a 10.1 
rating, while Rather's got a 9.9. Tom Brokaw's "NBC Nightly News," usually in 
third place, was there again, averaging an 8.9 for the week ending last Friday. 
It was the second time in four weeks that Jennings' newscast has topped the 
network news ratings.ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
