<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: COMPANY WORKING ON METRO RAIL FINED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Federal safety officials have fined a subcontractor $10,000 for allowing 
workmen in an unshored 12-foot trench on the Metro Rail project near downtown 
Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
Occupational Safety and Health Administration spokesman Frank Gravitt said 
Tecumseh Construction Co., which is doing electrical work for the subway 
system, was cited for knowingly placing employees in a life-threatening 
situation despite warnings from safety engineers. 
</P>
<P>
Gravitt said the employees were working early last month in a trench that was 
not properly sloped or shored. Inspectors found them at the bottom of the 
excavation without any protection against possible cave-ins or earth slides, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Tecumseh was warned of the potential danger by the safety engineer for 
Tutor-Saliba-Perini, general contractor for Metro Rail but failed to correct 
the situation, the OSHA spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
The subcontractor has 15 working days to correct the violations and pay the 
fines or to contest the citation before an OSHA review commission in 
Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
