<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
FIRST LADY GETS THYROID REMEDY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Barbara Bush underwent radioactive treatment today to destroy her thyroid gland 
because it is producing excess levels of hormones, a condition that has 
irritated her eyes and caused her to lose 18 pounds in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
"She's just fine, piece of cake, never broke her stride," her press secretary, 
Anna Perez, said after the President's wife returned to the White House after a 
two-hour stay at Walter Reed Army Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
The radiation was administered in an iodine solution sipped through a straw. 
Mrs. Bush said it was a colorless liquid that tasted like water, Perez 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
Doctors told Mrs. Bush, 63, that the only side effect she may suffer is a 
slight pain in the neck for several days. "She cracked jokes about that all 
day," Perez said. 
</P>
<P>
A White House statement said the procedure "has no significant side effects" 
and has been a standard treatment for 40 years for people suffering with Mrs. 
Bush's condition, known as Graves disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Barbara Bush smiles as she leaves hospital. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
